Agile Frameworks


1.	Scrum – The Scrum Framework is an empirical process where decisions are based on observations, experience and experimentation.
2.	Kanban – The Kanban Framework has it so the team has a continuous stream of work where the work items are pulled from a backlog.
3.	Extreme Programming (XP) – XP is an framework that focuses on producing higher quality software and higher quality of life for the development team.
4.	Feature Driven Development (FDD) – FDD is a framework that focuses on making progress on making features.
5.	Crystal – The Crystal Framework focuses on the team members and their interactions, mainly for short-term projects.
6.	Dynamic System Development Method (DSDM) – DSDM focuses on iterative and an incremental approach including continuous customer involvement.
7.	Rapid Application Development – This framework puts less emphasis on the planning process, and more so on the adaptive process, with prototypes being used.
8.	Adaptive Software Development (ASD) – This is a framework that emphasizes adaptability to respond to changing requirements and environments, with a focusing on learning.
9.	Disciplined Agile (DA) – It is used to guide the team members by using proven methodologies.
10.	Scaled Agile Framework (SAFe) – It promotes alignment, collaboration, and delivery across a large number of teams, trying to implement Agile across large environments.
11.	Large-Scale Scrum (LeSS) – Large scale scrum scaling agile across several teams all working on a singular project.
12.	Lean Software Development (LSD) – This framework is used to stream and optimize the software development process.

















Methodology	Framework
Agile’s methodology is to work on sections of the project in a 2 week sprint, communication with the business, customer, and dev teams consistently, as to minimize loss on time in case the customer wants something different or an issue comes up.	Scrum is a lightweight framework that helps teams and organizations generate value through adaptive solutions.


Roles	Development Team, Scrum master, product owner

Roles are sets of responsibilities given to the team or individuals.
Rituals	Sprint, Sprint Planning, Daily Scrum, Sprint Execution, Sprint Review, Sprint Retrospective, Product Backlog Grooming

Rituals represent active to be taken.
Artifacts	Definition of Done, Product Backlog, User Stories, Sprint Backlog, Burn-Down Chart, Task Board

Artifacts are documents that report some activity that will be performed by the team.
Rules	Rules are pre-defined behavior that teams or a control mechanism follows.



